			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I took an objectional look at this review and honestly it's not very good, and I said as much. He kept going back to the original EQ product and his complaints on it when he should have been writting about the expansion. <BR>
<BR>
 If this reviewer's complaints were well written and justified instead of the recycled complaints I hear from everyone that doesn't like EQ, I would have given it a second chance, but honestly this is a review for the EXPANSION. His complaints should have focused on that, instead he kept going back to the original EQ product and his issue's with it. He had a real problem with sticking to the expansion, and this really hurt his review in my opinion.<BR>
<BR>
 Also why I called him bias is simply when you go to buy any expansion for any game chances are you already really like the original product. Why have someone that obviously dislikes a game write a review on the expansion when he can't be objectional and tell people that are interested what they want to know? Expansion reviews should either be written by someone who enjoys the original product (as these are the people that are going to read the review most likely, and even be interested in the product to start with), or someone that can be objectional and tell people about it with an un-bias opinion. Just my 2 cents...
